    "what_description": "Cistus atlanticus is a perennial shrub native to the Atlantic coast of the Iberian Peninsula. It belongs to the family Cistaceae and is characterized by its small, white or pink, funnel-shaped flowers, often with a reddish tinge at the base, which are 4-6 mm in length and are arranged in a corymbiform inflorescence. The leaves are linear to lanceolate, 2-7 cm in length, and are covered with a dense, grayish tomentum on both surfaces. The plant typically grows up to 1-2 m in height and has a woody base with numerous, ascending branches. Cistus atlanticus is often found in sandy soils and scrublands, where it thrives in full sun and well-drained conditions.",
