    "constituents_description": "The most important healing constituents of Cistus atlanticus are rosmarinic acid, quercetin, kaempferol, caffeic acid and luteolin, which have been identified as flavonoids and phenolic acids. These compounds have been reported to exhibit antioxidant, anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial properties, contributing to the plant's wound healing, anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial activities. The antioxidant activity of rosmarinic acid, quercetin and kaempferol has been attributed to their ability to scavenge free radicals and chelate metal ions, thereby protecting cells from oxidative damage. Caffeic acid has been shown to have antimicrobial activity against several microorganisms, while luteolin has been reported to possess anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties. These bioactive compounds work synergistically to provide the plant's therapeutic effects, making Cistus atlanticus a valuable resource for the treatment of various health conditions.",
